Abstract = {Examined attitudes towards and etiology beliefs about mental illness. Ss were 126 1st-yr psychology undergraduate students (aged 17–45 yrs) in Auckland, New Zealand, who completed questionnaires before and after a series of 4 lectures concerning mental health problems given by 2 experienced clinical psychologists. Test materials administered included 8 items from the Mental Health Locus of Origin (MHLO); Results were evaluated according to Predictable–Unpredictable, Cold-hearted–Caring, and Endogenous–Interactional axes. Comparison of test scores showed that women's overall scores improved significantly; men's scores improved as well, but not significantly. Biological beliefs about the causes of mental health problems were related to negative attitudes, thereby confounding a common destigmatization policy linking mental health problems with medical illnesses. The amount of contact with those receiving psychiatric treatment was a strong predictor of positive attitudes, even stronger than acceptance of a psychological perspective. It is concluded that attitude changes are possible, at least in the short term. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)},
