Abstract = {Investigated staff–patient relationships (SPRs) on a continuing care, inpatient facility for patients (PAs; mean age 32.7 yrs) with severe mental illness. 20 staff members (SMs; mean age 31 yrs) were assessed for expressed emotion (EE) in regard to a client. Their spontaneous attributions for the PA's problems were also assessed, along with self-report SM and PA ratings of their expressed and perceived feelings and thoughts about their SM or PA counterpart. Although none of the SM were rated as fulfilling criteria for high EE, there was evidence of some variability in the quality of SPRs as assessed. PAs seemed to be sensitive to SM feelings for them: PA ratings of perceived feelings and thoughts from SMs were significantly correlated with SMs expressed feelings both from the CFI EE ratings and the direct self-report SM measures. SMs tended to view the behaviors of PAs they felt less positively disposed toward as more controllable, and this association between less benign explanations of behavior and a more critical attitude is consistent with the attribution research for familial caregivers. The more negatively perceived PA group was found to be more likely to have behavioral disturbances in the 7 mo after the relationship ratings were made. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)},
