@article{2001-06780-01020010401,
Abstract = {Investigates the relationship, well documented in other studies, between negative attitudes concerning mental health problems and biological and genetic causal beliefs. The literature shows that the 'mental illness is an illness like any other' approach to destigmatization, which has been the major effort in this area in the past 50 yrs, has failed to improve attitudes. The present study used a questionnaire of 469 1st-yr undergraduate students (17–42 yrs of age). Results replicate previous findings that the public tends to reject biological and genetic explanations of mental health problems in favor of psychosocial explanations focused on negative life events. It also confirms the previous findings concerning biological and genetic causal beliefs and negative attitudes. These attitudes include perceptions that 'mental patients' are dangerous, antisocial, and unpredictable, and reluctance to become romantically involved with them. The amount of reported personal contact with people who had received psychiatric treatment was correlated with positive attitudes. Authors recommend that destigmatization programs consider abandoning efforts to promulgate illness-based explanations, and focus instead on increasing contact with and exposure to users of mental health services. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)},
