Abstract = {Brought up by alienists long ago, the question of awareness of illness has once again struck psychiatrists because of its diagnostic and therapeutic implications. Using X. Amador's scale to assess Unawareness in Mental Disorders, the authors evaluated a cohort of 90 patients presenting with the following diagnoses: 37 suffered from schizophrenia with psychotic symptoms (PS), 14 from a schizoaffective disorder with PS, 18 from bipolar disorder with PS, 7 from unipolar disorder with PS, and 14 from unipolar disorder without PS. Statistical analysis of results confirmed that awareness of illness was significantly weaker in patients suffering from schizophrenia. Furthermore, causal attribution of symptoms and social consequences of disorder were significantly less correct in these patients. Finally, these results reflect those of recent studies by P. Bebbington and R. White (e.g., 1999) on social context of insight. The authors question whether poor insight in certain mental disorders is a symptomatic dimension or whether it is linked to social and cultural differences between the patient and his/her therapist. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)},
