@article{2002-18577-00920020901,
Abstract = {Examined the degree to which posttraumatic stress disorder (PTSD) symptoms account for fatigue in Dutch military veterans who returned from the peace operation United Nations Transitional Authority for Cambodia. 1,698 Dutch military veterans (mean ages 35.2-36.4 yrs) who participated in the peace operation completed surveys concerning fatigue, posttraumatic stress disorder, severe military experiences, subjective experiences, and physical and mental health. Results show that increased PTSD scores were found in 1.3% of Ss. There was no concordance between increased PTSD scores and reported fatigue. Ss with presumptive PTSD had more often left service, had more often been exposed to severe and potentially traumatic events, and more often reported a greater impact of the mission. These Ss reported more mental problems that they perceived to be service related and they held a stronger causal attribution to posttraumatic stress. It is concluded that presumptive PTSD cannot offer an explanation for fatigue in Cambodia veterans. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2018 APA, all rights reserved)},
