Abstract = {Upon the success of the Islamic revolution in 1979 in Iran, a wave of persecution was initiated against women for different reasons. Religious belief (being a Bahai) has been among the various reasons for the persecution of women in Iran. This dissertation reviews the role of religious belief as a reason for being persecuted and as an important factor for maintaining psychological stability and mental health after experiencing persecution among Iranian Bahai women. This study is intended to emphasize that the perceived cause for persecution might evoke a sense of conviction and integrity that might influence the tolerance level for the persecution. It was hypothesized that the severity of torture is a stronger predictor of Post Traumatic Stress Disorder for the female victims of non-religious persecution in Iran compared to those women who were persecuted for their religious beliefs. In this empirical study the participants (50 Iranian women between the ages of 30 to 65, who were in Iran for at least two years after Islamic Revolution) were interviewed by using the Persian version of the Harvard Trauma Questionnaire (HTQ). A relationship was found between the number of traumatic experiences and PTSD scores for the whole group, but the correlation between these factors did not hold when controlling for the religious group. T-tests revealed that those women who were persecuted for religious beliefs reported a significantly lower number of PTSD symptoms, despite a higher number of traumatic experiences. They also reported having a significantly weaker health condition, worse support system and were of older age than those persecuted for non-religious reasons. Using step-wise multiple regressions, other relevant predictors (e.g., demographic information) of severity of PTSD were also examined, but the reason for persecution was still found to remain as a significant predictor of PTSD above and beyond all these other factors. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 201