@masterthesis{2004-99004-12720040101,
Abstract = {Objectives. Although sensation and affect are well recognized as two principal dimensions of pain, it is still largely unknown how they function and interact in the experience of pain and what psychological factors may affect the specific aspects of pain experience. This study investigated the relationships of people's sensitivity to sensory stimuli (represented by sensory vigilance) and ability to process emotional information (represented by alexithymia status) to their experience of sensory, affective, and overall pains. Methods. Subjects were 159 individuals who reported some experience of pain within the week prior to their participation in the study. Subjects rated their sensory, affective, and overall pains on the Visual Analogue Scales (VASs) and the Pain Rating Index (PRI) of the McGill Pain Questionnaire, and completed questionnaires relating to sensory vigilance, alexithymia, psychopathology, pain features, and demographics. Hierarchical multiple regression analyses were conducted to determine the unique contributions of sensory vigilance and alexithymia to sensory, affective, and overall pains over and above demographic, pain feature, and psychopathological variables. Results. Sensory vigilance was significantly predictive of sensory pain based on the VASs, and sensory, affective, and total pains based on the PRI, when demographic, pain feature, and psychopathological variables were statistically controlled. Alexithymia status was not a unique predictor of any of the pain ratings. The results further indicated that sensory, affective, and overall pains based on the VASs and the PRI had very distinct profiles of unique predictors. VASs pain ratings showed greater associations with demographic variables, while PRI pain ratings had stronger relationships to sensory vigilance and pain causal attribution. Different combinations of unique predictors were also found between sensory and affective pains. Conclusion. Sensory vigilance is a significant predictor of pain experience over and above many other pain-correlates. Its potential influences on the experience of pain should be reflected in pain knowledge and treatment. Results also suggest that information about pain severity based on a single dimension and a single type of measure can be incomplete and problematic. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)},
