@masterthesis{2006-99014-21920060101,
Abstract = {The purpose of the current study was to further research on maternal attributions by addressing limitations in previous research. Attributions were coded from narrative interviews to limit problems such as unclear questionnaires and irrelevant hypothetical stimuli. Trait attributions were identified as well as causal attributions for specific experiences. Mothers' attributions were assessed for two children from each family to examine within family as well as between family differences in attributions based on gender and sibling status. Attributions for behaviors were coded separately from attributions for mental states to explore the importance of making this distinction. Coded attributions were correlated with several other parent and child variables to determine which are useful predictors of family functioning. Transcripts of interviews with mothers were reliably sorted into individual references to children's behaviors, mental states, or traits, and positive or negative valence was indicated. Causal attributions were then identified and reliably sorted into several categories that were compiled into scales similar to those addressed in previous research. Mothers made different types of attributions statements for older and younger siblings. They spoke more positively in general about older siblings, and made more negative, child-centered attributions about younger siblings. Mothers also differed in their attribution statements about boys compared with girls. More references were made to negative behaviors about boys, but boys were also described with more positive traits. Different patterns of causal attributions were also identified for boys and girls. Differences between attributions for behaviors and mental states were examined, and different patterns were apparent for boys and girls, although no sibling status differences were identified. Attribution scales were correlated with several family functions variables. Several important associations were identified. In general, more positive and less negative attributions were related to less harsh discipline by mothers, more mother-rated relationship satisfaction and less conflict, more positive and less negative mother-child interaction ratings, fewer child behavior problems, less negative child temperament ratings, more positive and less negative treatment by mothers, and better maternal responses to children's emotions. These patterns were generally more robust for older than younger siblings, and for girls as compared with boys. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)},
