@masterthesis{2008-99220-15920080101,
Abstract = {The following paper presents two separate investigations of the influence of knowledge and categorization in reasoning. Chapter 1 begins with an outline of relevant background ideas in categorization research and evidence of how knowledge influences categorization decisions. From here, Chapter 2 presents the first set of experiments. These experiments test how the acquiring of knowledge and formation of beliefs can influence the categorization of causal events. Experiment 1 of Chapter 2 presents participants with ambiguously defined causal events and tests how a causal belief can be used to categorize these ambiguous items. Experiment 2 explores how the strength of the belief that is acquired affects the categorization process. The influence of the categorization of ambiguous causal events on overall causal strength beliefs is tested in Experiment 3. Experiment 4 takes the idea of categorizing ambiguous causal events to a new arena and looks at how ambiguous temporal events are categorized. Chapter 3 presents a new experimental paradigm and looks at how previously acquired background knowledge affects reasoning about categories. Mental health clinicians who have great experience in dealing with mental disorder categories were tested to determine how this experience affects their memory for mental disorder categories. Clinicians' memory performance was compared to less experienced participant groups in order to determine how memory develops over the acquiring of experience and background knowledge. The implications of this research are discussed in the end of Chapter 3. After this discussion, the ideas that have been presented in this manuscript are summarized in Chapter 4. This final chapter also highlights implications for the research programs outlined in this document in real world reasoning. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)},
