Abstract = {Reviews the book, Schizophrenia:The positive perspective. Explorations at the outer reaches of human experience by P. K. Chadwick. (see record [rid]2008-14616-000[/rid]). The author of this book is a polymath, with doctorates in both the physical sciences and in psychology, an ex-patient with a diagnosis of schizophrenia, leading to a serious suicide attempt, a Pantheist, and for many years an academic in the area of the brain/ behavioral sciences. In structure, the book has three parts: The first part introduces the general approach, emphasizing that we should take more seriously first person accounts of major mental illness. The second part consists of autobiographical sections, with biographies of a number of persons he has met in practice as a community-based psychologist. The final part are reflections on what has gone before, including an interesting chapter on the interactions between CBT, psychoanalysis, existential therapy, spirituality and 'sense of self' in therapy. There are some areas where I hold back my assent, for instance, on occasion, where the author makes causal attributions. Trainee psychiatrists will regularly meet people with perspectives as diverse as those described herein. As a way into the inner world of such people, I believe this book to be of greater educational value than much standard description found in psychopathology or psychiatry textbooks. (PsycINFO Database Record (c) 2016 APA, all rights reserved)},
