@article{2011-03676-01020110301,
Abstract = {Comments on an article by Sylvie Groben and Constanze Hausteiner (see record [rid]2011-03676-009[/rid]). The paper addresses a very relevant topic. Causal attributions were recorded with two methods: an interview (spontaneous recall) and the Revised Illness Perception Questionnaire IPQ-R (prompted recall). Two aspects appear noteworthy to comment on. First, results show that subjects with somatoform disorders (SFDs) do not hold simplistic, monocausal illness attribution assumptions, but consider multiple causes as relevant to their symptoms. Overall, these findings are in line with some previous findings showing a considerable degree of mixed attributions in SFD even though a predominant somatic attribution style can be identified. Second, the authors shows that SFD patients were no more likely than non-SFD patients to exhibit somatic explanations for their symptoms. The authors conclude that somatic causal attributions should not be used as a positive criterion for future classifications as it lacks specificity. Actually, the current study does not provide support that a somatic causal attribution style has sufficient discriminant validity to qualify for a diagnostic criterion. Therefore, it is important that further prospective studies are performed to assess the relevance of symptom interpretation styles and of other psychological criteria and to investigate their impact on the course of the disorder — resulting in stronger empirical evidence for the selection of diagnostic criteria. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2020 APA, all rights reserved)},
