@masterthesis{2020-31777-02220200101,
Abstract = {Past research has established that different causal explanations for mental illness have small but unique effects on various components of mental illness stigma. Research has indicated that explanations that attribute mental disorders, such as schizophrenia, to biogenetic causes, as opposed to psychosocial causes, lead the public to direct less blame towards affected individuals, but to express greater pessimism regarding these individuals' prognosis. Given these mixed findings, variables that might mitigate negative effects or enhance the positive effects of various causal explanations for mental illness on stigma have become of interest. The present study investigated whether psychological inflexibility, which has been shown to be positively associated with mental illness stigma, moderates the relationship between causal explanations and multiple components of stigma. Participants included 558 adults, ages 18 or older, recruited through Amazon's Mechanical Turk. Participants answered questions about their personality and personal beliefs, read one of three different vignettes about a hypothetical character with schizophrenia, which attributed the character's condition to either biogenetic, psychosocial, or uncertain causes, and completed questions that assessed stigma towards the vignette character. It was hypothesized that, compared to those who were afforded a psychosocial explanation for the vignette character's condition, participants who were given a biogenetic explanation would ascribe less blame to the character but endorse greater prognostic pessimism. It was also hypothesized that more psychologically inflexible participants would be more stigmatizing of the vignette character than those who were less psychologically inflexible. Finally, it was hypothesized that psychological inflexibility would moderate the relationship between causal explanations and stigma. A one-way MANCOVA was conducted to test the study hypotheses and univariate tests of between-subject effects were conducted as follow up. Results indicated mixed support for study hypotheses; the different causal explanations did not impact stigma towards the vignette character and psychological inflexibility did not serve as a moderator, but psychological inflexibility did have an effect on multiple components of stigma. Implications of these findings for stigma reduction efforts and future research on the relationship between psychological inflexibility and stigma are discussed. (PsycInfo Database Record (c) 2020 APA, all rights reserved)},
